{
  "answer": "Several works in the Falsafa corpus—primarily ancient Indic Dharmaśāstra texts known as Smṛtis—discuss writing (typically termed *lekhya* or \"document\" in translation) explicitly as a legal or evidentiary medium. These texts treat written documents as one of the primary \"human proofs\" in judicial proceedings, alongside witnesses and possession (or inference/reasoning). They outline the characteristics, validity, defects, and procedural role of documents in disputes over debts, property, inheritance, and contracts. Divine proofs (e.g., ordeals) are secondary when documents exist.[^1][^2][^3]\n\n**Key works:**\n\n- **Bṛhaspati Smṛti**: Dedicates sections (e.g., 1.6) to the rules of documents, defining them as containing details like date, place, king's name, debtor/creditor, amount, and witnesses' signatures. They rank as one of three human proofs.[^4]\n\n- **Kātyāyana Smṛti**: Multiple chapters (23–29, 76) cover documents' strength as evidence, handwriting authentication, defects, and their equivalence to possession.[^5]\n\n- **Nārada Smṛti**: References documents (*lekhya*) in judicial matters like creditor-debtor disputes.[^6]\n\n- **Viṣṇu Smṛti**: Classifies documents into three kinds (e.g., royal, guild, private witnesses).[^7]\n\n- **Yājñavalkya Smṛti**: Includes a section (2: lekhyaprakaraṇam) on documents settled by consent.[^8]\n\n- **Manusmṛti**: Touches on evidentiary standards including writings implicitly via proofs and judgments.[^9]\n\nCharles Comte's *Traité de Législation* contrasts \"written laws\" (*lois écrites*) with unwritten/customary ones but does not treat writing itself as an evidentiary tool.[^10]\n\nNo other works (e.g., poetry, philosophy) address this topic.\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1 (/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-cb5a36).\n\n[^2]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, ch. 24 (/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-b4ce2a).\n\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1 (/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-510297).\n\n[^4]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1 (/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bbce9d).\n\n[^5]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, ch. 24 (/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/24/translation/#p-19695f).\n\n[^6]: *Nārada Smṛti*, ch. 1 (/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-cb5a36).\n\n[^7]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, ch. 7 (/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/07/translation/#p-510625).\n\n[^8]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, ch. 2 (/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-ff1854).\n\n[^9]: *Manusmṛti*, ch. 8 (/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-608b3f).\n\n[^10]: *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, ch. 11 (/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/11-chapitre-premier/translation/#p-7266f9).",
